Beach Volleyball


An Analysis of Olympic Beach Volleyball and Factors Linked to Player and Team Success



By: Katherine Krause, Caroline Tobin, Garrett Gerdau, Disha Gopal, and Tanay Singhal


Introduction

       For this project, our group chose to analyze beach volleyball: a fast-paced, dynamic sport that was fairly recently added to Olympic competition in 1996. In beach volleyball, there are two teams of two players on a sand court with a net in the middle. The goal for each team for each point is to ground the ball on the opponent’s side of the net. Each team is allowed up to three touches to return the ball over the net and no player can touch the ball twice consecutively unless following a blocking shot. Each point starts with a serve and ends when there is a fault, the ball goes out of bounds, or the ball is grounded. The team that wins the rally serves the following point and the four players serve in the same sequence for the duration of the match, switching servers each time a point is won by the receiving team. Additionally, the sport of beach volleyball is a series of best of three sets. The first two sets are played until one team reaches 21 points by two points. The third set, if needed, is played until one team reaches 15 points by two points.

      As beach volleyball was fairly recently introduced to the global stage of competition and we could find very limited public statistics on the sport, we decided that analysis of some of its key variables could provide value. We hypothesized that serving or receiving status plays a significant role in point conversion. Additionally, we predicted that the number of touches could prove to be an important variable in points won. We also were interested in finding a way to measure teamwork, which we viewed as essential in a partner-oriented sport like beach volleyball. In order to test these predictions, we compiled data focusing on 14 statistical variables through analyzing Olympic volleyball matches and a preview of this data can be seen below.

       When compiling our data, we wanted to analyze the highest level of play in the sport across different years and genders, in order to get a representative sample of Olympic beach volleyball. Each member watched a different volleyball match and recorded statistics on a various number of points totalling 187 points across five matches. The volleyball matches observed were as follows: Women’s USA vs. China 2012 London Semi-Final, Women’s USA vs. USA 2021 London Final, Men’s Norway vs. ROC 2021 London Final, Men’s Latvia vs. Qatar 2021 Tokyo Bronze Final, Women’s Latvia vs. Switzerland 2021 Tokyo Bronze Final. We gathered our data throughout the first week of the project and compiled it into a shared Google Sheets document.

       Each row in our dataset represents one of our 187 point observations. Each observation includes data from both the winning team (WT) and losing team (LT) of the overall match that was observed throughout each point. From our preview (Table 1), it can be seen that we collected data on instances of aces, touches, dives, spikes, and blocks within each point of play. Additionally, as can be seen in our full, raw dataset, we collected variables on serving team and player, team that won the point, move with which the point was won, and player who made the winning move. We recorded aces as an instance when a team’s serve was within bounds and the opponent could not return the serve. An instance of an ace can either occur during a point or not occur which we noted as “Yes” or “No.” Additionally, we defined touches for the winning and losing teams as the amount of times players on their respective teams made contact with the ball, not including the serve. Next, we defined dives for the winning and losing teams as the instances when players made contact with the sand in order to gain a touch on the ball. Then, we defined spikes for both teams as overhand shots made by players. Lastly, we defined blocks for both teams as instances when players jumped and hit the ball to prevent a scoring spike from the opponent.

Additionally, it can be seen that the mean number of touches for winning teams is lower than that of losing teams, possibly indicating a pattern in fast-paced play being a winning strategy.

Figure 1:


       Figure 1 (above) demonstrates the relationship between the serving team and winning team for each point. As you can see on the far left, during the USA v. China London 2012 Semifinal, when China served for the point, they won that point 5 times and lost the point 7 times. When the USA served during that same match, they won 4 of those points and lost 5 of them to China. The largest gap in serving/receiving performance between two teams who faced off against one another is evident in the 2012 Women’s Final match played by two USA teams. When the team of Misty May-Treanor and Kerri Walsh Jennings was serving, their opponents (Jennifer Kessy and April Ross) were able to maintain just over a 50% win rate. However, as is illustrated in the graph, Kessy and Ross were unable to keep their win rate anywhere near that of May-Treanor and Walsh Jennings’ when it was their turn to serve. Such a discrepancy in abilities during such a significant portion of points is something which could be looked at when teams are seeking to create a more well-rounded performance.


Figure 2:


       Figure 2 above illustrates the correlations between the various types of hits as well as total touches and total points won by a given team. All three of the types of hits observed (blocks, spikes, and dives) were shown to have a high positive correlation (each greater than 0.86) with the total number of points a team won, demonstrating that effective execution of both offensive and defensive hits is important to the overall success of a given point. Somewhat unexpectedly, the variable with the highest correlation (0.95) to total points scored was total touches. While we initially anticipated a high average number of touches to be indicative of an inability to effectively finish a point, it appears on the contrary to demonstrate an aptitude for keeping the ball in play for long enough to strike. The lowest two correlations in the bunch–indicated by the darkest blue–are those between spikes and dives (0.74) and spikes and blocks (0.73), which is interesting as it could indicate a discrepancy in how much focus players and teams give to training/practicing offensive vs. defensive play.

Insights
       a) Does Serving help a team in winning a point?

       For our first insight, we tried learning if the serving team has a competitive advantage and ends up winning the point out of the random points out of the whole match. Out of the 187 total points in our data, we observed that the serving team won the point only 69 times, which is 37% of the time. For that we created a table (3) and figure (1) that shows the number of times the team served and ended up winning a point. In order to gain a better understanding we also undertook a hypothesis test :

Null Hypothesis (H0) = Serving team wins the point
Alternative hypothesis (Ha) = Serving team does not win the point


       Since both of these variables were categorical, we tried to do a chi squared test which evaluates whether there is a significant association between the categories of the two variables.

test1 <- chisq.test(data\(Serving.team,data\)Team.won) test1$observed


       After using the above commands, we found the p value to be <2.2e-16 , X-squared value = 904.69 with df = 99. From this, we concluded to reject the null hypothesis.

       An interesting thing we learned from this insight was that serving does not give the team a competitive advantage of winning a point. The team that wins the point gets to serve, so it’s interesting to see that the serving team is less likely to win the point. Another interesting thing that we learned was that the serves constantly switched between teams rather than one team serving for most of the game. This makes sense from our insight of teams less likely to win the point when serving. The highest serving streak we saw was 4 serves until the team lost the point and the serve switched to the other team. On average, a team served 1.2 times before the serve switched to the other team.

       Given the high likelihood of losing the point when serving, there is a large incentive to score an ace without having to risk the opposing team returning the ball. 36.4% (68/187) of the serves in our dataset resulted in the opposing team immediately scoring with a spike using 3 or fewer touches (bump, set, spike) before the serving team could return the ball.

#Find probability (Opposing team (Non-Serving) has 3 or fewer touches and scores with a spike) = 68/187. Or, the likelihood your serve is returned with a winning spike by the opposing team.

       b) Distribution of players within a team and their closing moves

       For our next insight, we examined if teamwork played a role in winning the match by seeing if the team with both teammates contributing close to equal number of points tended to win. We hypothesized that the team that had both players contributing an equal number of points would win the match. For this, we collected the points scored by individual players in our random data set and calculated the probability based on the number of points we recorded for that team which can be seen in Illustration 1.

       We then compared the individual points of the players during the actual game and formed a hypothesis:

H0 = Teammates contribute equal number of points and leading them to win
Ha = One teammate gets more points than the other and they tend to win

 

       We then conducted a t test and found different p values for individual teams which were 0.704, 0.601, 0.723, 0.581, 0.543, 0.783, 0.698, 0.598, 0.732, 0.702–all greater than the 95% confidence interval which failed to reject the null hypothesis. Hence, our test results in teammates that had closer to equal contribution in points tended to win.

      In our random sample there was an outlier for the LAT V. QAT match where LAT had both teammates contributing an equal number of points. Our model predicted LAT to win the overall game, but QAT won the game by 2 points. Most of the losing teams had a large difference between the number of closing points by each teammate in our random sample compared to the actual game. Another interesting thing that we noticed from our random sample was that in beach volleyball the contribution of players is similar which means that both players train in all areas of serves and throws since it is a smaller team sport compared to other sports which have players with specific skills in which they train in. Because most points were gained by spikes, this difference in point distribution shows that in a team, one player is often closer to the net to the other. This could mean that drawing a team out of position if they tend to have a larger difference in number of closing points could help the opposing team win.

       Finally, when it comes to what we could have done better, we feel like instead of analyzing random points of various games, we could have compared values for 2 full games at the same level like Finals of Olympics etc. We could have cleaned our data more in order to avoid two different spellings for a particular term like spike and spikes. We could have also chosen a set of different variables for the game like Rally time, set time, match time, serve efficacy (standing serve, floating serve, and jump serve), setting efficacy (forearm, overhand, other, and 2nd attack), attack efficacy, and block efficacy. These could have been a perfect mix of categorical and numerical variables and would have helped us to understand the game and come up with better insights. We would have also made some minor aethetic changes to the paper such as unstretiching the player images in the chart.
